## Overview

This document covers the CI/CD pipeline design and infrastructure decisions I made for the `banking-finance` Spring Boot service. The goal was to keep things practical — automated deployments, no accidental pushes to production, and a setup that can actually scale without becoming expensive on day one.

The service is deployed on AWS EKS using Jenkins as the CI/CD engine. Docker images are stored in ECR. Every branch maps to a specific environment, and the pipeline handles building, testing, and deploying automatically.

---

## Part 1 – CI/CD Pipeline Design

### 1.1 Branching Strategy

I went with a straightforward three-branch model. Nothing overly complex — just something that maps cleanly to three environments.

```
feature/* or develop  →  qa         (dev testing)
staging               →  staging    (pre-prod validation)
main                  →  prod       (live users)
```

**How it works in practice:**

When a developer is building something new, they work on a `feature/` branch. That branch auto-deploys to the `qa` namespace on every push — so the team can always see what's in progress. Once the feature is done, it gets merged into `develop` (also goes to qa), then a PR is raised to `staging`, and finally another PR from `staging` to `main` for production.

The reason I kept `develop` going to qa and not a separate dev environment is purely cost. For a project at this stage, running four environments would be wasteful. QA and dev can share a namespace.

**Avoiding accidental prod deployments:**

Three things protect production:

1. `main` branch is protected on GitHub — no one can push to it directly. You have to raise a PR and get it approved.
2. The Jenkins pipeline has a manual `input` gate before any production deploy. Even if a merge happens, a human still has to click "Yes, Deploy to Production" in Jenkins before anything goes out.
3. The `main` branch in GitHub has a required reviewer set — so at minimum one other person has to approve the PR.

These three together mean production can only change intentionally.

---

### 1.2 Jenkins Pipeline

The pipeline has 8 stages. I kept each stage focused on one thing so it's easy to see exactly where something failed.

```
Stage 1 → Set Environment       (branch name → namespace)
Stage 2 → Checkout              (pull code from GitHub)
Stage 3 → Run Tests             (mvn test — stops here if any test fails)
Stage 4 → Build JAR             (mvn package)
Stage 5 → Build Docker Image    (docker build)
Stage 6 → Push to ECR           (push image to AWS ECR)
Stage 7 → Deploy to EKS         (kubectl apply → rollout)
Stage 8 → Health Check          (hit /actuator/health, rollback if down)
```

**On a PR (not merged yet):**
Jenkins only runs stages 1–4. It builds and tests, but does not deploy. This gives developers fast feedback without touching any environment.

**On merge:**
All 8 stages run. For production merges, stage 7 pauses and waits for manual approval.

**Rollback strategy:**
If the health check in stage 8 fails, the `post { failure }` block automatically runs `kubectl rollout undo`. This reverts to the previous deployment within about 30 seconds. I also use build numbers as image tags (not `latest`) so every image is traceable and any version can be re-deployed manually if needed.

