## Part 2 – Infrastructure Design

### 2.1 Compute Choice – Why EKS

I evaluated three options:

| Option | Pros | Cons | Decision |
|--------|------|------|----------|
| EC2 only | Simple, full control | Manual scaling, no self-healing | ✗ |
| ECS | Easier than EKS, AWS-native | Less flexible, harder to migrate later | ✗ |
| EKS | Standard Kubernetes, auto-scaling, self-healing | More setup upfront | ✓ |

I went with EKS because the team is already familiar with Kubernetes concepts, and it gives us horizontal pod autoscaling out of the box. If load spikes, new pods spin up automatically. If a pod crashes, Kubernetes restarts it. EC2 can't do either of those things on its own.

Node type is `t3.medium` — 2 vCPU, 4 GB RAM. Enough for a Spring Boot app in development and staging. Production can scale the node group up if needed.

---

### 2.2 Container Registry – ECR

ECR was the natural choice since everything else is on AWS. No cross-cloud authentication complexity. IAM roles handle access — no passwords to manage. Images are private by default and tag immutability can be turned on to prevent overwriting released versions.

---

### 2.3 Networking

```
Internet
    ↓
AWS Load Balancer  (created automatically by K8s Service type: LoadBalancer)
    ↓
EKS Worker Nodes  (inside VPC, private subnets)
    ↓
Pods (banking-finance containers)
```

The pods themselves are not directly exposed to the internet. The Kubernetes Service of type `LoadBalancer` provisions an AWS Network Load Balancer which is the only public-facing entry point. This keeps the attack surface small.

For a production hardening step, I'd move to an ALB Ingress Controller and add a WAF rule in front of it — but for this phase, the NLB approach is sufficient.

---

### 2.4 Secrets & IAM

No passwords in code. No passwords in environment variables baked into images.

The setup:
- Jenkins EC2 has an **IAM Role** attached → gets temporary credentials automatically
- That role has permissions for ECR (push images) and EKS (deploy)
- Application secrets live in **AWS Secrets Manager**
- Pods retrieve secrets at runtime via the AWS SDK

This way there is nothing sensitive in the Git repository, nothing sensitive in the Dockerfile, and nothing sensitive in the Kubernetes YAML files.

---

### 2.5 Logging & Monitoring

- **CloudWatch Container Insights** is enabled on the EKS cluster — this gives CPU, memory, and pod-level metrics out of the box with no extra setup.
- **Application logs** go to stdout from the Spring Boot app and are automatically collected by CloudWatch Logs via the Fluent Bit daemonset that EKS installs by default.
- For alerting, CloudWatch Alarms are set on pod restart count and CPU utilization.

This is intentionally lightweight. The priority was getting deployments working reliably. A proper observability stack (Prometheus + Grafana) is the next step once the pipeline is stable.

---

## Key Decisions Summary

| Decision | Choice | Why |
|----------|--------|-----|
| CI/CD tool | Jenkins | Already running, team familiar |
| Container registry | AWS ECR | Same AWS account, IAM auth |
| Compute | AWS EKS | Auto-scaling, self-healing |
| Deployment type | Rolling | Zero downtime, no extra cost |
| Secrets | AWS Secrets Manager | Nothing sensitive in code |
| Credentials | IAM Role on EC2 | No hardcoded keys |
| Prod protection | Branch protection + manual gate | Two-layer safety |
| Image tagging | Build number | Every build traceable |
